Headline.Para: Egypt Strongman's Heavy Lift: Getting People to Vote; President Sisi, his re-election all but certain, seeks a robust show of support at polls this week

LeadPara.Para: CAIROâ€”Egyptians will begin voting Monday to choose between President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi and a party leader who proudly supported him days before he entered the campaign, Moussa Moustafa Moussa.
"Why would I vote? To choose between who and who? I never even heard of the other guy," said a Cairo hairdresser before the polls opened.

TailParas.Para: Mr. Sisi faces the unusual challenge of convincing the public to participate in a three-day election in which the outcome isn't in doubt. As in the re-elections of other strongman rulers around the world, most of Mr. Sisi's challengers have been jailed or sidelined. The opposition has called for a boycott.
A low turnout could be an embarrassmentâ€”undermining the president's claim of popular support and hindering efforts to fend off international criticism of his human-rights record.
Mr. Sisi has called for a high turnout, casting it as a patriotic duty.
"I need the whole world to see us in the street voting. Choose what you want, but it's important that Egyptians vote," he said at a campaign event on Wednesday.

Little campaigning took placeâ€”though banners with Mr. Sisi's face appeared throughout Cairo, many of them paid for by individual supporters who often pair their faces with the president's. Mr. Sisi's backers held few rallies, and the president appeared mainly at scripted official events.

In the absence of a traditional campaign, Mr. Sisi appears to be relying on nationalist and pro-military messages to compel voters to the polls. In Cairo's Tahrir Square, the epicenter of the revolt that ousted President Hosni Mubarak in 2011, Mr. Sisi's face appears in two star-shaped billboards while a huge screen plays a montage of tanks and soldiers in action.
"Sisi is the right person to choose even if there were dozens of other candidates because he's the man building this country and strengthening the army," said Ibrahim Al-Baz, 73 years old.
A 63-year-old former general, Mr. Sisi came to power after leading the 2013 military coup that overthrew President Mohammed Morsi, an Islamist leader who had won a democratic election a year earlier.
In 2014, Mr. Sisi won 97% of the votes in an election in which less than half of eligible Egyptians took partâ€”even after the government extended voting for an extra day.
Now far removed from the pro-democracy protests of 2011, Mr. Sisi's government has intensified a crackdown on opponents.
Mr. Sisi said he would have preferred to have more candidates on the ballot and blamed political parties for not fielding contenders, in an interview on state television this month.
"It's not my fault," he said.

Though no reliable polling data exist, there are signs that Mr. Sisi's popularity has waned as a result of rising prices of basic goods and chronic economic problems such as joblessness among Egypt's young population. More than a third of Egyptian young people are unemployed, according to the International Labor Organization.

Yet aspiring candidates have been detained or have withdrawn from the race citing an unfair political climate. In January, authorities arrested a former military chief of staff, Sami Anan, days after he launched a presidential campaign, accusing him of incitement against the armed forces. Mr. Anan remains in military detention; his representatives have rejected the accusations as politically motivated.

"In the current climate of resurgent authoritarianism, the Sisi regime acts with impunity and with absolutely zero concern over the ramifications," said Michael Hanna, an Egypt expert at the Century Foundation, a policy institute in New York.
Mr. Sisi has denied such accusations. "People are free to express their opinion," he said in the TV interview.

Since coming to power, Mr. Sisi has cast himself as a force for stability in a region shaken by war and political crises, but his government has struggled to stop attacks by Islamic State militants that have killed hundreds of soldiers and civilians. An offensive against the militants in the Sinai Peninsula continues.

Mr. Sisi, playing up his image as a bulwark against regional extremism, has also won a grudging acceptance from some European leaders and words of support from President Donald Trump, who once called Mr. Sisi "a fantastic guy."
When asked at a campaign event in January about the possibility of losing, the president laughed.

The symbolic nature of the exercise isn't lost on voters. "I have to work two jobs to make a living and I'll lose a whole day's wages if I go vote," said Mohamed Dahabi, an office assistant in Cairo. "It won't matter because we already know who will win."
Out of Contention
Several would-be contenders in Egypt's presidential election have been jailed, detained, and otherwise sidelined
* Ahmed Shafiq This former prime minister dropped his 2018 candidacy after he was deported from the United Arab Emirates in December and held under apparent house arrest in a Cairo hotel.
* Sami Anan The former military chief of staff said he was running in January; days later he was arrested and charged with incitement against the armed forces, a charge his representatives deny.
* Khaled Ali A prominent human-rights lawyer, he withdrew citing government arrests of his campaign workers.
* Mohamed Anwar Sadat A former member of parliament and nephew of the former president of the same name, Mr. Sadat cut his campaign short citing an unfair political climate.
* Ahmed Konsowa An army colonel sentenced to six years in prison in December on charges of expressing political opinions as a serving officer after he launched a presidential campaign.
